{
    "id": "interrogative-pronouns-grammar",
    "title": "Unit 7 Learn Greek Grammar Masterclass: Interrogative Pronouns and Adverbs",
    "curriculum_id": "unit-7-grammar",
    "voices": {
        "en": "en-AU-WilliamMultilingualNeural",
        "gr": "el-GR-AthinaNeural",
        "gr_en": "en-US-AvaMultilingualNeural"
    },
    "script": [
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "Welcome... to the Learn Greek Grammar Masterclass for Unit 7: Interrogative Pronouns and Adverbs. To have a real conversation... you need to be able to ask questions. Who... What... Where... Why... and When. In Greek... some of these are simple... and one of them is a shape-shifter that confuses every student. I'm William... and here with me is Athina. Athina... what are the 'Big Five' question words?"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Γεια σας!"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "Let’s start with the static ones. These never change their shape."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Πού..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "for Where."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Πότε..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "for When."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Πώς..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "for How."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Γιατί..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "for Why. And remember..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Γιατί"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "also means 'Because'! You use the same word for the question and the answer."
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "That's convenient. Question:"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Γιατί;"
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "Answer:"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Γιατί..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "something something. Now... let’s talk about the tricky ones. 'Who' and 'What'."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "This is the shape-shifter."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Ποιος."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "It means 'Who'... but it also means 'Which'. And because it’s an interrogative pronoun... it MUST agree with the gender of the person you are asking about."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Ποιος..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "for a man."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Ποια..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "for a woman."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Ποιο..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "for a thing."
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "So if I see a woman in the distance and want to ask 'Who is she?'... I must use"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Ποια;"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Ακριβώς!"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Ποια είναι αυτή;"
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "But wait... there’s a shortcut. I've heard Greeks say"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Τι."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "Yes!"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Τι"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "is the universal 'What'. It never changes gender. You can use it for almost anything."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Τι κάνεις;"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "... 'What are you doing?'."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Τι είναι αυτό;"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "... 'What is this?'."
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "So"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Τι"
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "is your best friend when you’re in a hurry. Now... one last 'Masterclass' secret about 'Who'. What happens in the Accusative case?"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "It follows the noun rules! If you are asking 'Whom' do you see... the"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "ς"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "drops and we add an"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "ν."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Ποιον βλέπεις;"
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "It’s perfectly consistent with everything we learned in Unit 5. This has been a short but essential unit. You can now navigate the world... ask for directions... find people... and understand the 'Why' behind it all. Practice these five words tonight. Excellent work... we’ll see you in Unit 8: Possession and the Genitive Case."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Γεια σας!"
        }
    ]
}